---
description: Core architectural constraints for the Media Library Manager project
alwaysApply: true
---

# Stack
- Monorepo with `apps/web` and `apps/api`
- Frontend: Next.js + TypeScript + Tailwind
- Backend: NestJS + TypeScript
- Database: MongoDB
- Shared domain types belong in `packages/types`

# Product constraints
- Private login-first app
- Two buckets only in v1: `catalog` and `wishlist`
- Media types: `movie`, `tv`, `album`, `book`, `game`
- Ratings are read-only external metadata only
- No email verification or password reset
- Barcode scanning is best-effort candidate matching, never assume exact auto-match

# Architecture rules
- Frontend must never call third-party metadata providers directly
- Backend owns auth, sessions, provider integrations, normalization, barcode lookup, caching, and permission checks
- Do not replace MongoDB with Postgres
- Do not use Prisma
- Do not use NextAuth/Auth.js
- Do not collapse frontend and backend into one app unless explicitly asked

# Data model rules
- Use `users`, `sessions`, `library_entries`, `media_records`
- Do not use SQL-style subtype tables like `item_as_cd` or `item_as_game`
- Keep user-owned collection state separate from provider-imported metadata

# Working style
- Before large edits, produce a plan with affected files
- Prefer complete working code over pseudocode
- Keep types explicit and reusable
- After major edits, run relevant typecheck/build commands